<h1>🔀 Extra — If Statements: Only Sometimes</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> If / Elif / Else · <strong>Course:</strong> Extra Worksheet · <strong>Time:</strong> about 30 minutes</p>
<p>Some code runs <strong>every time</strong>. Some code runs <strong>only if</strong> something is true. On paper you will read <code>if</code> code, predict it, fix it, and explain it in your own words.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Keep these words handy: <strong>condition</strong>, <strong><code>==</code></strong>, <strong><code>else</code></strong>, <strong><code>elif</code></strong>, <strong>indent</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each snippet. Write what you think it will print.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">score = 7
if score &gt; 5:
    print(&quot;You win!&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Does "You win!" print? Why?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">age = 10
if age == 12:
    print(&quot;You are 12.&quot;)
else:
    print(&quot;You are not 12.&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What prints?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">weather = &quot;rain&quot;
if weather == &quot;sun&quot;:
    print(&quot;Wear sunglasses&quot;)
elif weather == &quot;rain&quot;:
    print(&quot;Bring umbrella&quot;)
else:
    print(&quot;Just go outside&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What prints? Why did it skip the first line?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each snippet is broken. Read what it should do, then rewrite it so it works. Explain why the original was wrong.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — This should check if <code>score</code> equals <code>10</code>. Instead it always prints "Perfect!", even when <code>score</code> is <code>3</code>.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">score = 3
if score = 10:
    print(&quot;Perfect!&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> checking equal uses two of something.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — This should print "Too cold" only when <code>temp</code> is below <code>0</code>. Right now it prints "Too cold" no matter what <code>temp</code> is.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">temp = 15
if temp &lt; 0:
print(&quot;Too cold&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the line inside the <code>if</code> needs to be pushed in.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Explain the Code 📖</h2>
<p>Here is a complete program that checks a player's score and prints a message.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">score = 8

if score &gt;= 9:
    print(&quot;A+ player!&quot;)
elif score &gt;= 5:
    print(&quot;Good job!&quot;)
else:
    print(&quot;Keep practicing!&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What prints when <code>score</code> is <code>8</code>? Walk through why it picks that branch.</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>What would print if <code>score</code> was <code>9</code>? What about <code>2</code>?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why does the program stop checking once it finds a true condition?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

